    "id": 4,
    "date": "Oct 2025",
    "title": "Using Lovable to explore 10 versions in an hour",
    "body": "The bottleneck in early product design isn't ideas — it's the cost of making ideas visible. Lovable collapses that cost so much that my entire process changed.",
    "tags": [
      "Prototyping",
      "AI"
    ],
    "logos": [
      "https://www.google.com/s2/favicons?sz=64&domain=lovable.dev"
    ],
    "thumbBg": "#FFF1F2",
    "image": null,
    "fullContent": "<p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\">We needed to add an AI summary section to an activity card. The catch: users land on a diary page with ten of these cards. Very limited time. A lot of information competing for attention.</p><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\">The design had to stand out enough to be noticed. But not so much that it disrupted the workflow. Progressive disclosure. The problem was figuring out what that actually looked like in practice.</p><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\">There were a lot of options. Chips in different colors. Text format. Different card sizes. Show more button. Scroll within the box. Expand the whole card. Each combination changed the feel completely.</p><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\">Static Figma gets you part of the way. But the moment someone asks \"what happens when you scroll inside this?\" or \"how does the expand feel?\" you're stuck. You can fake it with overlays, but it takes hours to build and it still isn't real.</p><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\">So I built it in Lovable instead. Multiple versions, all in one prototype. At the top: a version switcher. Click v1, v2, v3, v5. Try each one. Scroll, tap, expand. Feel the difference.</p><figure><img src=\"data:image/gif;base64,\"><figcaption data-empty=\"false\">Interactive prototypes</figcaption></figure><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\">In our design review with the PM and engineers, nobody had to imagine anything. They just clicked.</p><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\">That session answered questions we'd been circling for a while. Text format turned out to be the most flexible. It scaled better across different card sizes and didn't feel as noisy as chips. The show more button felt cleaner than in-card scrolling. Things that would have taken another round of Figma revisions got decided in the room.</p><p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n</p><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\">Figma is great for showing what something looks like. It's not great for showing how something feels. For interaction-heavy decisions, a real prototype with multiple live versions beats a polished static file every time.</p>",
    "contentType": "html",
    "group": "building"
