    "id": 2,
    "date": "Dec 2025",
    "title": "What I learned shipping my first PR with Cursor",
    "body": "The first real thing I shipped with Cursor was a loading state for an AI agent. It sounds small. But going from idea to merged PR solo taught me more about AI-assisted dev than any tutorial.",
    "tags": [
      "Cursor",
      "Engineering"
    ],
    "logos": [
      "https://www.google.com/s2/favicons?sz=64&domain=cursor.sh"
    ],
    "thumbBg": "#E8ECF2",
    "image": null,
    "heroImage": "/uploads/cursor-first-pr-hero.png",
    "hideHeroInPanel": true,
    "fullContent": "<p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\">Our AI assistant had a thinking UI. When it worked, users just saw loading states. \"Fetching CRM data.\" \"Loading Gong calls.\" No context. No visibility. Just spinners.</p><p></p><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\">My design task was to improve it. I created a proposal in Figma and a demo in Lovable. The structure was clean and linear: search sources first, then reasoning, then generate output. Three steps. Everything in order.</p><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\"></p><figure><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\"><figcaption data-empty=\"false\">My initial suggestion created by Lovable</figcaption></figure><p></p><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\">Engineers were too busy to implement it. So I downloaded Cursor, had my teammate engineer help me set up the dev environment, and tried to build it myself.</p><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\"><b>That's when I discovered the problem with my design.&nbsp;The real model doesn't follow a fixed order.&nbsp;</b></p><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\">Sometimes it reasons first. Sometimes it searches first. Sometimes both, several times over. With my linear structure, if the model started with reasoning, the UI would show step 2 loading while step 1 hadn't happened yet. And for reasoning-heavy models, there weren't 3 steps. There were 6. Sometimes more. My design had no room for that.</p><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\">So I rebuilt it differently. Instead of a predefined structure, each tool call became its own step. Each reasoning block became its own step. The UI follows what the model actually does, not what I assumed it would do.</p><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\"></p><figure><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\"><figcaption data-empty=\"false\">Built with actual model output</figcaption></figure><p></p><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\">The PR merged the same day. It was my first PR. Also the first PR ever shipped by a designer at Nooks. The CEO was surprised: \"Are you putting up PRs?\"&nbsp;</p><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\"></p><figure><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\"><figcaption data-empty=\"false\">Kudos from the engineer who owns this&nbsp;</figcaption></figure><p></p><b>The real lesson wasn't about Cursor.&nbsp;</b><strong>You can't design AI interfaces with static assumptions.</strong>&nbsp;<br><br><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\">The model doesn't follow your script. Different questions change the order. Different models change the depth. A design that maps out every step in advance will always be wrong for some inputs.</p><p class=\"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]\"></p><figure><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\"><figcaption data-empty=\"false\">My first published PR</figcaption></figure><p></p>",
    "contentType": "html",
